[birds chirping]

00:01.585 --> 00:03.962
- Daddy,
don't forget the popsicles.

00:04.046 --> 00:06.048
- We were supposed
to bring popsicles?

00:08.675 --> 00:10.010
You are not my child.

00:15.182 --> 00:17.976
<i>Before kids, you have</i>
<i>a strong sense of identity</i>

00:18.060 --> 00:20.145
<i>based on, you know,</i>
<i>your hobbies and interests.</i>

00:20.229 --> 00:22.231
- ASTRID:
<i>The bands you like or your job.</i>

00:22.314 --> 00:23.690
- JAMES:<i> But as you focus</i>
<i>on raising kids,</i>

00:23.774 --> 00:27.361
<i>it feels like</i>
<i>you become more generic.</i>

00:27.444 --> 00:29.947
- ASTRID:<i> People see you</i>
<i>as just another mom or dad.</i>

00:34.076 --> 00:36.870
Mrs. Jellinek wrote
an entire recipe book?

00:36.954 --> 00:38.705
This is so elaborate.

00:38.789 --> 00:40.249
This kid made enchiladas?

00:40.332 --> 00:41.375
VIV: That's Gerardo.

00:41.458 --> 00:44.795
He stepped on my shoe
but he wants to get married.

00:44.878 --> 00:46.755
- Just tell Gerardo
to slow his roll.

00:46.839 --> 00:48.423
<i>You hope some part</i>
<i>of your identity</i>

00:48.507 --> 00:49.883
<i>lives on through your kids,</i>

00:49.967 --> 00:52.302
<i>your ethnic and cultural</i>
<i>heritage for example,</i>

00:52.386 --> 00:54.137
<i>but, uh, even that can get lost.</i>

00:54.221 --> 00:56.557
All these recipes
are so traditional.

00:57.683 --> 01:00.644
And we made
Rice Krispie Treats.

01:00.727 --> 01:01.770
Viv?

01:01.854 --> 01:02.938
What?

01:03.021 --> 01:04.857
- Why does
it say you're Indigenous,

01:04.940 --> 01:06.024
you're part Indian.

01:06.108 --> 01:08.193
- VIV: We don't use
that word anymore.

01:08.277 --> 01:09.570
We are Indian.

01:09.653 --> 01:12.364
- You're not
supposed to say that.

01:20.038 --> 01:21.456
Hey, Felix, great game.

01:21.540 --> 01:22.457
Hey, what do you say, Felix?

01:22.541 --> 01:23.959
- Thanks, coach.
- Yeah.

01:24.042 --> 01:25.878
You know, I'm really--I'm really
surprised we beat Green

01:25.961 --> 01:28.338
because, you know,
they're a lot better than Red.

01:28.422 --> 01:30.299
Well, they didn't have Felix.
He's our secret weapon.

01:30.382 --> 01:32.384
Yeah. Secret weapons,
they run in our family.

01:32.467 --> 01:34.678
I was pretty good.
My dad was a homerun king

01:34.761 --> 01:36.555
and Mom, very athletic.

01:36.638 --> 01:38.307
Felix's mom, not my dad's mom.

01:38.390 --> 01:40.267
But she can jump really high.

01:40.350 --> 01:41.351
- Dad.
- Yeah.

01:41.435 --> 01:42.728
You know, we have
the same batting stance.

01:42.811 --> 01:44.271
He knows it's all in the legs.

01:44.354 --> 01:45.564
- It goes like this.
- Okay.

01:45.647 --> 01:47.191
See you next game, slugger.

01:47.274 --> 01:49.776
- Yeah, yeah. We'll see you.
We'll be there.

01:49.860 --> 01:51.737
Hey, what do you think about
Berney bats for us...

01:51.820 --> 01:53.488
and just call each other that

01:53.572 --> 01:55.532
like, like Joey Bats, you know.
How's that sound?

01:55.616 --> 01:56.867
- FELIX: Dad?
- JAMES: Uh-hmm?

01:56.950 --> 01:58.160
When is baseball over?

01:58.243 --> 01:59.786
What? What do you mean
when's baseball over?

01:59.870 --> 02:02.456
- Season just started, pal.
- My tummy hurt the whole game.

02:02.539 --> 02:04.333
- You get two homeruns
on a bad tummy,

02:04.416 --> 02:05.834
that's like the Jordan flu game.

02:08.712 --> 02:10.339
Hey.

02:10.422 --> 02:12.382
You know, I had a bad tummy too
before games sometimes,

02:12.466 --> 02:14.635
- you know what really helped?
- Um, not playing?

02:14.718 --> 02:16.011
Something more delicious.

02:16.094 --> 02:19.014
- Ice cream!
- Yeah! Small scoop though.

02:19.097 --> 02:21.266
Sensitive gut
also runs in the family.

02:21.350 --> 02:23.101
Let's go, buddy!

02:23.185 --> 02:25.521
- All right. What are
we reading tonight, huh?

02:25.604 --> 02:26.813
Something with a real story,

02:26.897 --> 02:28.732
something that's not
about a licensed toy?

02:28.815 --> 02:31.401
- Read my cookbook!
- Ah, your cookbook. Yes.

02:31.485 --> 02:33.195
I've been meaning to talk to you
about your cookbook.

02:33.278 --> 02:35.113
- I'm in a real book,
like Barbie.

02:35.197 --> 02:36.240
Or like a scientist.

02:37.366 --> 02:38.325
Okay.

02:38.408 --> 02:41.495
So I'm part Indian, which again,
is different than Indigenous.

02:41.578 --> 02:43.372
And because I'm part Indian,

02:43.455 --> 02:45.165
that means
that you're part Indian too.

02:45.249 --> 02:47.417
People from India are Indian.

02:47.501 --> 02:49.962
- Dad is Indian?
- ASTRID: No, not Daddy,

02:50.045 --> 02:52.673
but Felix
and, and Dawn auntie and Corey.

02:52.756 --> 02:54.800
- Uncle Bo's
a citizen of the world.

02:54.883 --> 02:56.510
- Yeah.
Uncle Bo's also from Winnipeg.

02:56.593 --> 02:57.636
- And I'm from India.
- ASTRID: Well, you're not

02:57.719 --> 02:59.137
from India exactly.

02:59.221 --> 03:00.556
Nanima was born in England,

03:00.639 --> 03:02.474
but her parents
were born in India.

03:02.558 --> 03:04.643
And you and me are part Indian.

03:04.726 --> 03:06.103
I thought we were Canadian.

03:06.186 --> 03:07.271
ASTRID: Yeah, we are.

03:07.354 --> 03:09.982
It also is important
where your family lived.

03:10.065 --> 03:13.151
So if Charlotte
from Karate lived in India,

03:13.235 --> 03:14.570
she would be Indian too?

03:14.653 --> 03:17.531
- Charlotte from Karate lived
in India for like 10 years,

03:17.614 --> 03:18.782
and then did a lot of paperwork.

03:18.866 --> 03:20.951
She could technically
become a citizen, I guess.

03:21.034 --> 03:22.953
But being Indian is...

03:25.038 --> 03:26.123
not skin color.

03:26.206 --> 03:27.374
If you like spicy food?

03:27.457 --> 03:31.128
- Sure. Yes. Yup.
Let's go with that. That one.

03:31.211 --> 03:32.921
So a quick recap,

03:33.005 --> 03:37.050
you are English, Scottish,
and East Indian, and Canadian.

03:37.134 --> 03:38.886
And I'm a cat named Ocean.

03:40.095 --> 03:42.139
- Indian Ocean?
- VIV: No.

03:53.066 --> 03:55.277
- So the ethnicity talk
went well?

03:55.360 --> 03:56.904
I confused us both so much.

03:56.987 --> 03:59.239
- Viv forgot she was even human.
- Uh-hmm.

04:00.532 --> 04:02.242
- ASTRID: What's that for?
- Felix.

04:02.326 --> 04:04.912
Our big guy is carrying
the whole team on his shoulders

04:04.995 --> 04:06.788
- and it's upsetting his tum-tum.
- Yeah.

04:06.872 --> 04:08.749
He barely even
touched his dinner, poor guy.

04:08.832 --> 04:10.292
- Pre-game jitters
runs in the family.

04:10.375 --> 04:12.711
All elite athletes get them.

04:12.794 --> 04:15.339
- Do all elite athletes
also get knee pain from driving?

04:15.422 --> 04:17.633
- We are both
sensitive stomached athletes.

04:17.716 --> 04:18.717
It happens all the time.

04:18.800 --> 04:21.220
Cowboy Cerrone,
he puked before every big fight.

04:21.303 --> 04:23.347
Glenn Hall,
notorious pre-game vomiter,

04:23.430 --> 04:25.599
and Bill Russell the goat,
he hurled before every big game.

04:25.682 --> 04:28.310
- But those people
are paid to puke.

04:28.393 --> 04:29.895
Felix is supposed
to be doing this for fun.

04:29.978 --> 04:33.857
- And throwing up
makes room for all the fun.

04:33.941 --> 04:35.442
Don't say that to our kids.

04:39.071 --> 04:40.697
- MS. JELLINEK: Out you go, Viv.
Sorry you had to wait.

04:40.781 --> 04:42.574
Took her a while
to find her coat.

04:42.658 --> 04:44.701
- Yeah, that's not her coat,
or her shoes.

04:44.785 --> 04:45.827
Oh no.

04:45.911 --> 04:48.163
Viv, go find your things.

04:49.164 --> 04:51.166
- She does that sometimes.
- It's cool.

04:51.250 --> 04:52.709
Some of the stuff
she brings home is pretty nice.

04:52.793 --> 04:54.127
- She also pretends
to feed sandwiches

04:54.211 --> 04:55.337
to her shoes sometimes.

04:55.420 --> 04:57.631
As long as no one's eating glue,
I feel pretty good.

04:57.714 --> 05:00.259
- Yeah, totally.
She's, she's also really cool

05:00.342 --> 05:02.386
and smart,
and strong, right?

05:02.469 --> 05:04.012
She's great.

05:04.096 --> 05:06.682
- Love the class recipe book,
by the way.

05:06.765 --> 05:08.350
I just had one small issue.

05:08.433 --> 05:11.562
- Sometimes an eggplant emoji
just means eggplant, you know?

05:11.645 --> 05:12.729
Uh, no.

05:12.813 --> 05:16.191
I think--I think Viv told you
that she was Indigenous.

05:17.734 --> 05:18.819
She's not.

05:18.902 --> 05:21.029
I just--I would hate
for anyone to be offended.

05:21.113 --> 05:23.949
So if you wouldn't mind,
reprinting Viv's page--

05:24.032 --> 05:27.244
- Can I be real with you?
I paid for the printing myself.

05:27.327 --> 05:30.497
Crazy, I know,
but we are severely underfunded.

05:30.581 --> 05:32.875
Did you get
my email about donating pencils

05:32.958 --> 05:34.710
- and spare Kleenex?
- It's just one page.

05:34.793 --> 05:36.879
- Exactly.
Parents are only gonna read

05:36.962 --> 05:38.463
their own kid's page, right?

05:38.547 --> 05:40.424
You probably can't even name
another recipe from the book.

05:40.507 --> 05:43.343
- Well, the pasta puttanesca
really stood out.

05:43.427 --> 05:46.471
That's Italian
for pasta of the prostitutes.

05:46.555 --> 05:48.724
- Yeah.
- Look, maybe we just remove

05:48.807 --> 05:50.434
Viv's page from the book.

05:50.517 --> 05:52.352
- What?
- ASTRID: Hey,

05:52.436 --> 05:54.104
nice coat. It's a keeper.

05:54.188 --> 05:56.607
I wanna be in the book.

05:56.690 --> 05:57.900
All right. New plan.

05:57.983 --> 05:59.985
If I pay for the printing,

06:00.068 --> 06:02.404
can you make sure that gets to
all the other parents? Please?

06:02.487 --> 06:06.241
- Can you sweeten the deal
with, say, some Kleenex?

06:06.325 --> 06:10.037
- Yes.
We failed you as a society.

06:10.120 --> 06:11.246
Hmm.

06:18.795 --> 06:20.547
- ASTRID: Is it
gonna be much longer, Dawn?

06:20.631 --> 06:21.548
DAWN: Not much,

06:21.632 --> 06:24.593
but it's important
to prepare sushi properly.

06:24.676 --> 06:26.970
I heard about a man
who developed an infection

06:27.054 --> 06:30.098
from eating tainted sushi
and had his arm amputated.

06:30.182 --> 06:31.308
I'm gonna eat my own arm.

06:31.391 --> 06:32.726
COREY: Knowing the history

06:32.809 --> 06:36.146
feeds the stomach and the mind.

06:36.230 --> 06:38.524
- Speaking
of super authentic meals,

06:38.607 --> 06:40.484
I was actually thinking
that I should teach the kids

06:40.567 --> 06:41.777
one of our traditional
family recipes.

06:41.860 --> 06:44.112
Rice Krispie Treats?

06:44.196 --> 06:46.990
They were your favorite.
The secret's the Rice Krispies.

06:47.074 --> 06:49.034
- Uh, no. I was thinking
chana bhaturas.

06:49.117 --> 06:50.410
- NISHA: And smell up
the house with frying?

06:50.494 --> 06:51.703
Just order from Little India.

06:51.787 --> 06:53.080
Hey, Viv, dining room.

06:53.163 --> 06:54.623
- Okay.
- BO: Yo. I help Corey

06:54.706 --> 06:55.791
with his cooking videos.

06:55.874 --> 06:57.209
I can teach you
to make a mean aloo gobi.

06:57.292 --> 06:58.210
- Nope.
- Big no.

06:58.293 --> 06:59.586
